definition.p:
The linear combination of the vectors \vvec_1,\vvec_2,\ldots,\vvec_n with scalars c_1,c_2,\ldots,c_n is the vector
c_1\vvec_1 + c_2\vvec_2 + \ldots + c_n\vvec_n\text{.}
The scalars c_1,c_2,\ldots,c_n are called the weights of the linear combination.

li.p:
      When c=1 and d=-2, we find

	1\vvec -2 \wvec =
	\twovec{0}{-3}\text{.}

We find the linear system for the weights:
\begin{alignedat}{3} 2c \amp {}+{} \amp 1d \amp {}={} \amp 3 \\ 1c \amp {}+{} \amp 2d \amp {}={} \amp 0 \\ \end{alignedat}
If we construct the corresponding augmented matrix and determine its reduced row echelon matrix, we find the weights c=2 and d=-1.

In the same way, we construct a linear system for the weights whose augmented matrix is
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 2 \amp 1 \amp 1.3 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp -1.7 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1.43 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -1.57 \\ \end{array}\right] \text{,}
which shows that there are weights that produce the desired linear combination. The same will happen for any vector \bvec that we ask to write as a linear combination of \vvec and \wvec.

statement.p:
This leads to the equations

  \begin{aligned}
  c\twovec3{-1} + d\twovec43
  \amp =
  \twovec{-11}{-18}    \\ \\
  \twovec{3c}{-c} + \twovec{4d}{3d}
  \amp =
  \twovec{-11}{-18}    \\ \\
  \twovec{3c+4d}{-c+3d}
  \amp =
  \twovec{-11}{-18}    \\ \\
  \end{aligned}

Equating the components of the vectors on each side of the equation, we arrive at the linear system
\begin{alignedat}{3} 3a \amp {}+{} \amp 4b \amp {}={} \amp -11 \\ -a \amp {}+{} \amp 3b \amp {}={} \amp -18 \ \end{alignedat}
This means that \bvec is a linear combination of \vvec and \wvec if this linear system is consistent.

li.p:
Consider the following linear system.
\begin{alignedat}{4} 3x_1 \amp {}+{} \amp 2x_2 \amp {}-{} x_3 \amp {}={} \amp 4 \\ x_1 \amp \amp \amp {}+{} 2x_3 \amp {}={} \amp 0 \\ -x_1 \amp {}-{} \amp x_2 \amp {}+{} 3x_3 \amp {}={} \amp 1 \\ \end{alignedat}
Identify vectors \vvec_1, \vvec_2, \vvec_3, and \bvec such that the question "Is this linear system consistent?" is equivalent to the question "Can \bvec be expressed as a linear combination of \vvec_1, \vvec_2, and \vvec_3?"

We find the linear system
\begin{alignedat}{4} 4c_1 \amp {}+{} \amp c_2 \amp {}-{} \amp 2c_3 \amp {}={} \amp 0 \\ \amp \amp -3c_2 \amp {}+{} \amp c_3 \amp {}={} \amp 1 \\ 2c_1 \amp {}+{} \amp 3c_2 \amp {}+{} \amp c_3 \amp {}={} \amp 2 \\ c_1 \amp {}+{} \amp c_2 \amp \amp \amp {}={} \amp -2 \\ \end{alignedat}
with corresponding augmented matrix
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 4 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -3 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This shows that the linear system is inconsistent so there are no such weights c_1, c_2, and c_3. This means that \bvec is not a linear combination of \vvec_1, \vvec_2, and \vvec_3.

This is the same as asking if the linear system corresponding to the following augmented matrix is consistent:
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\ -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
From the reduced row echelon form, we see that the system is consistent, which means that \bvec can be expressed as a linear combination of \vvec_1, \vvec_2, and \vvec_3. Moreover, there are infinitely many ways in which we can do so.

We find the augmented matrix
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ -2 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 8 \\ 1 \amp -1 \amp -2 \amp -4 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -4 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This shows that \bvec can be expressed as a linear combination of \vvec_1, \vvec_2, and \vvec_3 in exactly one way.
